<subSubSection id="F423559568AE41D610DFB7CDC7922703" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="4668AC17175C8C61622F23872E1E6C37" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Diagnosis and description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6F62AD1D150144CF673CCD16455FF65C" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Females: In females of this subgenus, the mandible always has a conspicuous, partial cutting edge in the second interspace (reduced in 
<taxonomicName id="1B16509FE6425F380E85997593A48A4C" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Megachile) genalis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="genalis" subGenus="Megachile">Megachile genalis</taxonomicName>
, which is easy to diagnose due to the thickened buldge at the base of the mandible: 
<bibRefCitation id="B1F0C448EC3125DC58939693AA942AF4" author="Amiet, F" journalOrPublisher="Fauna Helvetica" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 274" title="Apidae 4: Anthidium, Chelostoma, Coelioxys, Dioxys, Heriades, Lithurgus, Megachile, Osmia, Stelis." volume="9" year="2004">Amiet et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A1C9176234D3F0E9C0FCE371DFF89CB4" author="Scheuchl, E" journalOrPublisher="Apollo Books, Stenstrup, Denmark" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" title="Illustrierte Bestimmungstabellen der Wildbienen Deutschlands und Oesterreichs. Band II: Megachilidae - Melittidae. Second, revised edition." year="2006">Scheuchl 2006</bibRefCitation>
), and no visible cutting edge in the third interspace (Figs 32-34). The mandible is mostly 5-toothed with the distance between both upper teeth subequal to the distance between the other teeth (not clearly so in 
<taxonomicName id="FFC1A557C6F133B1331547D57A5C951D" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) genalis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="genalis" subGenus="M.">M. genalis</taxonomicName>
) (Figs 1, 32); in some species teeth 4 and 5 are poorly separated (Fig. 33). In 
<taxonomicName id="26EC56B24F362F9C27A06DF3993B22E2" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) bombycina" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bombycina" subGenus="M.">M. bombycina</taxonomicName>
, the mandible is elongate and 4-toothed but the partial cutting edge in the second interspace is well visible (Fig. 34). In most species, the clypeus is flat or slightly depressed preapically, and there the punctures are coarse and the interspaces wide, shiny (Fig. 32); this condition is not found in 
<taxonomicName id="F509904A2754D1E96DDD2397D3DE28DC" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) lapponica" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lapponica" subGenus="M.">M. lapponica</taxonomicName>
Thomson, 1872, in which the clypeus is densely punctured (Fig. 33), and in 
<taxonomicName id="F23388634312ED143768D01B35818614" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) bombycina" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bombycina" subGenus="M.">M. bombycina</taxonomicName>
, in which the clypeus is modified, short, laterally truncate and medially produced to a blunt triangular process, and with its apical margin forming a wide, smooth and slightly concave area (Fig. 34). In the female sex, many species of 
<taxonomicName id="33D230439BED016903FCA471CB62190D" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Megachile)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Megachile">Megachile</taxonomicName>
s. str. are sculpturally similar to 
<taxonomicName id="DE96809018734E4F1478366D8655B790" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Anodonteutricharaea)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Anodonteutricharaea">Anodonteutricharaea</taxonomicName>
; in the former, the scopa is mostly orange basally and rarely white, while in 
<taxonomicName id="4238D3DDDC0E00DDDDD5760A941C360D" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Anodonteutricharaea)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Anodonteutricharaea">Anodonteutricharaea</taxonomicName>
the scopa is mostly white to yellowish white; and 
<taxonomicName id="DAEAB1A67D31BD58ACD7862455A564F3" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Anodonteutricharaea)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Anodonteutricharaea">Anodonteutricharaea</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the presence of two unmodified setae on the pretarsal claws; in 
<taxonomicName id="5139F5B8B8FD2017DFB9F3941CECFCFE" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Megachile)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Megachile">Megachile</taxonomicName>
s. str., the basal seta is modified to a thicken process, as in 
<taxonomicName id="A0E3F04FF52B7DC85544F7973B2F65BC" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Eutricharaea)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Eutricharaea">Eutricharaea</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="10A73F38A301ECB3CCDD932A101BE50B" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Xanthosarus)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Xanthosarus">Xanthosarus</taxonomicName>
(as in Fig. 5). Males: Males of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="7B15DFF8034516F9B79903749A01B79B" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Megachile)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Megachile">Megachile</taxonomicName>
s. str. are rather homogenous both in their sculpture and in genitalic structures, and often difficult to identify. All males of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="6864FAE9CB3055DAFA4E0F1D070A9274" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (Megachile)" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Megachile">Megachile</taxonomicName>
s. str. lack a front coxal spine, although in some species (
<taxonomicName id="7941E75E2A5C95F420A6ACBBC7650D72" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) ligniseca" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ligniseca" subGenus="M.">M. ligniseca</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="320D920A4A097EB61FDF9537674EAAFA" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) melanopyga" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanopyga" subGenus="M.">M. melanopyga</taxonomicName>
Costa, 1863), the front coxa forms a weak angle. The mandible is always 3-toothed, mostly with inferior projection (lacking in 
<taxonomicName id="D626526AF41AF3BBB103C3CED6C9B149" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) pilicrus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilicrus" subGenus="M.">M. pilicrus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="5F09B4A6A84999AC54FB125B8EABD8B3" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) armenia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armenia" subGenus="M.">M. armenia</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="666DA2043B1BE1BF978F2C94892B8772" originalValue="Tkalců">Tkalcu</normalizedToken>
, 1992). In most species the disc of T6 is devoid of white or light pubescence (except in 
<taxonomicName id="4E50C9DB5CA0EA7390154323E0A2471A" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) pyrenaea" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyrenaea" subGenus="M.">M. pyrenaea</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="5FFBD4D96C3A9F9BA70D6F0D481DBDB1" originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
, 1890, 
<taxonomicName id="822E57C59B57093EABE98B56B2D2D61A" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) armenia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armenia" subGenus="M.">M. armenia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DF9A10A9AC945EF6DF656A4B5FDE2E41" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) pilicrus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilicrus" subGenus="M.">M. pilicrus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A5175E84CF0D3A4A0FFCB88F1E525249" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae (M.) melanopyga" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanopyga" subGenus="M.">M. melanopyga</taxonomicName>
), the preapical carina of T6 is never denticulate, although there is a lateral tooth at the lateral margin of T6 (Fig. 42). T7 is either small or exposed, but mostly unmodified (without tooth apically). The gonostylus is always simple, never bifid apically (Fig. 42).
</paragraph>
